<p dir="ltr"><strong><em>Students will complete the following questions to practice the skills they have learned in this lesson.</em></strong></p>
<p dir="ltr">In the following exercises, determine whether each ordered pair is a solution to the system.</p>
<p>1. \(3x + y &gt; 5\)<br/>
</p>
<p dir="ltr" role="presentation">     \(2x-y\leq10\)<br/></p>
<p dir="ltr"> </p>
<p dir="ltr">a. \((3,−3)\) </p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>Answer: </strong>Yes<br/>
When you substitute the values into the inequalities the results are:</p>
<p>\(\begin{array}{rcr}
  3(3) + (-3) &gt; 5 &amp;   &amp;2(3) − (-3)≤10 \\
  6&gt;5 \checkmark &amp;   &amp; 9≤10 \checkmark
  \end{array}\) </p>
<p>The point is true for both inequalities, so the ordered pair (3, -3) is a solution to the system.</p>
<p dir="ltr">b.  \((7,1)\)</p><p><strong>Answer: </strong>No<br/>
When you substitute the values into the inequalities the results are:</p>
<p>\(\begin{array}{rcr}
  3(7) + (1) &gt; 5 &amp;   &amp;2(7) − (1)≤10 \\
  22&gt;5 \checkmark &amp;   &amp; 13≤10 ❌
  \end{array}\) </p>
<p>The point must be true for both inequalities to be a solution to the system. Since (7,1) is not true for both systems, it is not a solution.</p>
<br/>
<p dir="ltr"> 2. \(4x − y &lt; 10\)<br/><span>    \(−2x + 2y &gt; −8\)</span><br/></p>
<p dir="ltr"> </p>
<p dir="ltr">a.  \((5,−2)\) </p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>Answer: </strong>No<br/> 
When you substitute the values into the inequalities the results are:</p>
<p>\(\begin{array}{rcr}
  4(5) - (-2) &lt; 10 &amp;   &amp;-2(5) + 2(-2)&gt;−8 \\
  22&lt;10 ❌ &amp;   &amp; -14&gt;-8 ❌
  \end{array}\) </p>
<p> Since (5,-2) is not true for either system, it is not a solution.</p>
<p dir="ltr">b. \((−1,3)\)</p><p><strong>Answer: </strong>Yes<br/>
When you substitute the values into the inequalities the results are:</p>
<p>\(\begin{array}{rcr}
  4(-1) - (3) &lt; 10 &amp;   &amp;-2(-1) + 2(3)&gt;−8 \\
  -7&lt;10 \checkmark &amp;   &amp; 8&gt;-8 \checkmark
  \end{array}\) </p>
<p>The point is true for both inequalities, so the ordered pair (-1,3) is a solution to the system.</p>
<br/>
<p>3.  \(y\;&gt;\;\frac23x\;-\;5\)<br/><span>      \(x\;+\;\frac12y\;\leq\;4\)<br/></span></p>
<p dir="ltr"> </p>
<p dir="ltr">a.  \((6, −4)\) </p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>Answer: </strong>No<br/>
When you substitute the values into the inequalities the results are:</p>
<p>\(\begin{array}{rcr}
  -4 &gt; \frac23(6)-5 &amp;   &amp;6+\frac12(-4)≤4 \\
  -4&gt;-1 ❌ &amp;   &amp; 4≤4 \checkmark
  \end{array}\) </p>
<p>The point must be true for both inequalities to be a solution to the system. Since (6,-4) is not true for both systems, it is not a solution.</p>
<p dir="ltr">b. \((3, 0)\)</p><p><strong>Answer: </strong>Yes<br/>
When you substitute the values into the inequalities the results are:</p>
<p>\(\begin{array}{rcr}
0 &gt; \frac23(3)-5 &amp;   &amp;3+\frac12(0)≤4 \\
0&gt;-3 \checkmark &amp;   &amp; 3≤4 \checkmark
\end{array}\) </p>
<p>The point is true for both inequalities, so the ordered pair (3,0) is a solution to the system.</p>
<br/>
<p>4.  \(y\;&lt;\;\frac32x\;+\;3\)<br/><span>      \(\frac34x\;-\;2y\;&lt;\;5\)</span></p>
<p dir="ltr"> </p>
<p dir="ltr">a. \((−4,−1)\)</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>Answer: </strong>No<br/> 
When you substitute the values into the inequalities the results are:</p>
<p>\(\begin{array}{rcr}
  -1 &lt; \frac32(-4)+3 &amp;   &amp;\frac34(-4)-2(-1)&lt;5 \\
  -1&lt;-3 ❌ &amp;   &amp; -1&lt;5 \checkmark
  \end{array}\) </p>
<p>The point must be true for both inequalities to be a solution to the system. Since (-4,-1) is not true for both systems, it is not a solution.</p>
<p dir="ltr"> b. \((8, 3)\)</p><p><strong>Answer: </strong>Yes<br/>
  When you substitute the values into the inequalities the results are:</p>
<p>\(\begin{array}{rcr}
    3 &lt; \frac32(8)+3 &amp;   &amp;\frac34(8)-2(3)&lt;5 \\
    3&lt;15 \checkmark &amp;   &amp; 0&lt;5 \checkmark
    \end{array}\) </p>
<p>The point is true for both inequalities, so the ordered pair (8,3) is a solution to the system.</p>
<br/>
<p>5.  \(6x − 5y &lt; 20\)<br/>      \(-2x+7y&gt;-8\)<br/></p>
<p dir="ltr">a. \((1, −3)\) </p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>Answer: </strong>No<br/>
When you substitute the values into the inequalities the results are:</p>
<p>\(\begin{array}{rcr}
      6(1)-5(-3) &lt; 20 &amp;   &amp;-2(1)+7(-3)&gt;-8 \\
      21&lt;20 ❌ &amp;   &amp; -23&gt;-8 ❌
      \end{array}\) </p>
<p> Since (1,-3) is not true for either system, it is not a solution.</p>
<p dir="ltr">b. \((−4, 4)\)</p><p><strong>Answer: </strong>Yes<br/>
  When you substitute the values into the inequalities the results are:</p>
<p>\(\begin{array}{rcr}
    6(-4)-5(4) &lt; 20 &amp;   &amp;-2(-4)+7(4)&gt;-8 \\
    -44&lt;20 \checkmark &amp;   &amp; 36&gt;-8 \checkmark
    \end{array}\) </p>
<p>The point is true for both inequalities, so the ordered pair (-4,4) is a solution to the system.</p>
